\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Direct Calculation of Double Counting Rate for Neutron Multiplicity Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Wilfried Monange 
\backslash
thanks{Institut of Radioprotection and Nuclear Safety} 
\backslash
and Grégory Caplin 
\backslash
thanks{ORANO at IRSN when the work was prepared} 
\backslash
and Olivier Jacquet 
\backslash
thanks{Subcontractor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neutron density in nuclear system is subject to fluctuations that arise
 from nuclear random process.
 For sub-critical systems with large number of neutrons these fluctuations
 are usually small enough so that the well known Boltzmann equation is valid
 and the system is correctly described by mean quantities.
 This is no more true with a law neutron density that implies predominantly
 neutron fluctuations over average values obliging the use of other techniques
 to correctly describe the neutron population.
 Among them, the Neutron Multiplicity Counting (NMC) methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NMC Ensslin,NMC Robba"

\end_inset

 focus on correlated time neutrons (i.e.
 neutrons belonging to the same fission chain) detections for sub-critical
 system using mean single count rate (i.e.
 mean count rate of detection), double count rate (i.e.
 mean count rate of time correlated pairs of detections), triple count rate
 (i.e.
 mean count rate of time correlated triples of detections), etc.
 In this way NMC is based on higher-order moment of the counting distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually NMC values obtained by simulation are calculated with algorithms
 very similar to those used with real detectors and therefore only make
 use of detection times.
 Depending on the simulation tools, the calculation of these values is performed
 directly inside the simulation code or outside 
\emph on
via
\emph default
 output files (List-mode like) and post-processing programs.
 This approach is referred here to as the 
\emph on
analog method.

\emph default
 As this method require exact simulation of the transport of neutrons, i.e.
 analog calculation, classical Monte Carlo techniques for variance reduction
 (Russian roulette, splitting etc.), which only preserve first order moment
 (mean quantities), cannot be used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a consequence and although dating back to the early nuclear era, the
 use and study of NMC techniques has been for many years limited by the
 performance of computers that struggled to simulate the entire neutron
 population of an experiment.
 Thanks to modern computers a number of barriers have been raised and these
 techniques are now regularly used for the reactivity assessment of low
 power ADS reactors, non-destructive assay of special nuclear material,
 sub-critical benchmarks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Multiplicity benchmark,BErPW Benchmark,BErPNi Benchmark,SCRaP Benchmark"

\end_inset

, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, NMC simulations can still be very CPU time consuming under certain
 circumstances such as configurations with huge calculation time for neutron
 transport or when NMC values with large time scale are required.
 Some methods have been developped to solve this problem such as variance
 reduction techniques 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Szieberth"

\end_inset

 or sensitivities estimation throw eigen values calculations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hutchinson sensitivity"

\end_inset

.
 This paper proposes another approach based on the use of analog simulation
 tools taking advantage of an additional information provided by the code
 : the fission chain identifier (or history identifier) to which a detection
 belongs.
 This information makes it possible to identify the correlated detections,
 i.e.
 resulting from the same fission chain.
 This approach will be referred to the 
\emph on
direct method.
 
\emph default
The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the direct identification of correlated detections.
 This paper focuses on the calculation of the single counting rate, the
 double counting rate and the so called Feynman-Y curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feynman,Croft"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first part recalls the 
\emph on
analog method
\emph default
 methodology, then the theory of the direct method is described and is applied
 to a real experiment in the last part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Analog method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calculation of NMC values has been extensively described in the literature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Uhrig,Hutchinson1"

\end_inset

.
 This section recall the basis using the Hage-Cifarelli formalism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cifarelli"

\end_inset

 in order to keep consisteing with the 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
 formalism in the next section.
 During an NMC simulation, neutron detections are time-tagged and stored
 into a file creating the so called 
\emph on
signal
\emph default
 (which therefore contains a set of detection times).
 In a second step, the post processing divid this 
\emph on
signal
\emph default
 into equal samples of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 For each of them the number of events are counted and binned into a histogram
 called the Feynman histogram.
 This histogram therefore represents the occurrence probabilities of various
 multiplets (i.e., 1 detection, 2 detections, etc.) occurring within a specified
 samples width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Several methods exist to split the signal, Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Feynman_hist"

\end_inset

 shows the construction of the Feynman histogram with consecutive samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/feynman_histo.png
	lyxscale 75
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Feynman_hist"

\end_inset

The post-processing divid a signal into samples (a) and construct the feynman
 histogram (b).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From these the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

 values representing the number of times 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 detections are found in samples are deduced.
 This can be repeated for multiple samples widths resulting in multiple
 Feynman histograms.
 The NMC values are finally calculated with the following formulas:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{1}(\tau)=\frac{\underset{k}{\sum}k\,c_{k}(\tau)}{\underset{k}{\sum}c_{k}(\tau)}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{2}(\tau)=\frac{1}{2}\frac{\underset{k}{\sum}k(k-1)c_{k}(\tau)}{\underset{k}{\sum}c_{k}(\tau)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{1}(\tau)=\frac{m_{1}(\tau)}{\tau}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{2}(\tau)=\frac{1}{\tau}\left(m_{2}(\tau)-\frac{1}{2}m_{1}(\tau)^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y(\tau)=2\times\frac{Y_{2}(\tau)}{Y_{1}(\tau)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}$
\end_inset

 stand for the single and double counting rates for samples of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 being the first two reduced factorial moments as expressed in the Hage-Cifarell
i formalism.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the Feynman-Y value also equal to the ratio of the variance to the mean
 in the number of neutron detections in samples of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 minus unity : 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)=\frac{Var\left(C_{k}(\tau)\right)}{Mean\left(C_{k}(\tau)\right)}-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is simply the count rate, his value should remain constant regardless the
 samples width value (as long as it is sufficiently large to avoid statistical
 effect) and equal to a named value 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 allows to adjust the amount of detections coming from the same fission
 chains (i.e.
 correlated detections) taken into account.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 tends towards zero the probability of having correlated detections also
 tends towards zero as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 increases, more and more correlated detections are taken into account leading
 to an increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 At first only correlated detections from prompt neutrons are taken into
 account, then from all neutrons (prompt + delayed).
 This is shown by the presence of two plateaus on the Feynman curve.
 Further increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 do not add more correlated detection and both 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

 tend to their asymptotic values respectively named 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/feynman_curve.png
	lyxscale 75
	width 8cm

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Feynman-Y curve as a function of the samples width (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to reduce uncertainties the number of samples used must be large
 (often several thousand).
 If one want to cover delayed neutron, large samples are required (at least
 100 seconds) and the simulated signal can required unacceptable CPU time
 or experiment duration.
 As a consequence, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 are in practice estimated throw formulas depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

, making these values dependent of both the samples width (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

) and the underlying theory:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{2}(\tau) & =\frac{1}{\omega(\tau)}\,Y_{2}(\tau)\label{eq:R2_omega}\\
Y_{\infty}(\tau) & =2\,\frac{R_{2}(\tau)}{R_{1}}\nonumber \\
\omega\,(\lambda,\tau) & =1-\frac{1-e^{-\lambda\tau}}{\lambda\tau}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Wehre 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the neutron lifetime which includes slowing-down time
 in the detector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for the NMC values to be meaningful and usable for other measures
 (calculation of total multiplication for instance), the experiment must
 be in a steady state, i.e.
 the power remains constant over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Direct method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be the mean rate of source events (i.e.
 the mean number of histories per time unit) and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the probability for an history to create 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections.
 Both values comes from simulation results.
 In particular, the association of each detection with the fission chain
 identifier makes it possible to calculate the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

quantity.
 That being said, for a stationary process the mean rate of detections from
 histories creating 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is 
\begin_inset Formula $S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 denotes the binomial coefficient.
 Summing over all possible numbers of detections gives the single rate of
 detections:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{Y}_{1}=S\sum_{N=1}^{\infty}p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{1}\label{eq:y1_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this formula as well as for the following, the circle denotes values
 calculated using the 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
.
 One may note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{1}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on any samples width values and thus 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
it is equal to its asymptotic value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{1}$
\end_inset

.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 To be consistent with formulas presented in section 2 the expected number
 of detections per samples 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{1}\,\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same approach is then applied for the double counting rate.
 Considering the mean rate of correlated pairs triggered by the 
\emph on
ith
\emph default
 detection of histories creating 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is 
\begin_inset Formula $S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N-i}^{1}$
\end_inset

, the mean double counting rate created by histories having 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\cdot p_{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}C_{N-i}^{1}=S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account all histories with any number of detections gives the
 asymptotic mean double counting rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{R}_{2}=S\sum_{N=2}^{\infty}p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{2}\label{eq:r2_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contrary to the 
\emph on
analog method,
\emph default
 the 
\emph on
direct method 
\emph default
gives directly access to the asymptotic double counting rate without the
 need of intermediate formulas.
 As a consequence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

do not depends of neither 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 or an underlying theory but only on the number of simulated histories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now interested in the calculation of the non-asymptotic value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Let's consider a first detection in the time range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{1},t_{1}+dt_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 and a second one inside 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{2},t_{2}+dt_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}<t_{2}$
\end_inset

, the average number of correlated pairs of detections 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 between two correlated detections distant of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}-t_{1}$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}=\mathring{R}_{2}\cdot pdf(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $pdf$
\end_inset

 the probability density function of the time intervals between any pair
 of detections of an history i.e.
 the auto-correlation function.
 Once again the fission chain identifier provided by the simulation code
 allows the direct calculation of the PDF.
 The average counts in the time ranges 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{1},t_{1}+dt_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{2},t_{2}+dt_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 that are uncorrelated pairs of detections is equal to the product of the
 average detection rate: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}=\mathring{R}_{1}{}^{2}\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{a}$
\end_inset

 gives the well-known Rossi-Alpha distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}Q(t_{2}-t_{1})dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2} & =\left(Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})+Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\right)dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathring{R}_{1}^{\,\,2}+\mathring{R}_{2}\cdot pdf(t_{2}-t_{1})\right)dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 refer to the words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accidental
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as often used with the Rossi-Alpha method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NMC Ensslin"

\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 defined, one can now calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{2a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{2r}$
\end_inset

 which respectively correspond to the expected number of uncorrelated or
 correlated pairs of detection in samples of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This is achieved by summing for each detection occurring at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}\leqslant\tau$
\end_inset

 the second detections occurring at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}\leqslant\tau$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathring{m}_{2r}(\tau) & =\int_{0}^{\tau}dt_{1}\cdot\int_{t_{1}}^{\tau}Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\mathring{R}_{2}\int_{0}^{\tau}cdf(t)\cdot dt
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:m2r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mathring{m}_{2a}(\tau) & =\int_{0}^{\tau}dt_{1}\cdot\int_{t_{1}}^{\tau}Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\mathring{R}_{1}^{\,\,2}\,\tau^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf$
\end_inset

 the cumulative density function of the time intervals between any pair
 of detections of an history.
 Combination of the previous equations gives the final expression of the
 doubles counting rate as calculated with the 
\emph on
direct method 
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau) & =\frac{\mathring{m}_{2r}(\tau)}{\tau}\\
 & =\frac{\mathring{R}_{2}}{\tau}\,\intop_{0}^{\tau}dt\cdot cdf(t)
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:y2_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the definition of the Feynman-Y values as two times the ratio
 between the double and simple counting rate remains valid so that no specific
 derivation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{Y}=2\,\frac{\mathring{R}_{2}}{\mathring{R}_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{Y_{\infty}}(\tau)=2\,\frac{Y_{2}(\tau)}{Y_{1}}\label{eq:y_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Back to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:m2r"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\tau}cdf(t)\cdot dt$
\end_inset

 behaves asymptotically like 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf(\tau)$
\end_inset

 approaches unity.
 Let us now define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that approaches unity as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 tends towards infinity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 the number of pairs of detections in a gate of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 contains both correlated and uncorrelated pairs of detections, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2r}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, can also be written as the following :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}m_{2r}(\tau) & =m_{2}(\tau)-m_{2a}(\tau)\\
 & =m_{2}(\tau)-\frac{1}{2}m_{1}^{\,\,2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is now possible to express the asymptotic doubles counting rate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The deduced equation is similar to the one obtained in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:R2_omega"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{R}_{2}(\tau)=\frac{\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau)}{w(\tau)}=\frac{m_{2}(\tau)-\frac{1}{2}m_{1}^{2}}{\tau\cdot w(\tau)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above reasoning does not differentiate between sources.
 For instance, if histories are created by both spontaneous fissions and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 combines these two types of sources.
 However, for practical reasons it is sometimes interesting to differentiate
 sources in simulations: one may perform a set of simulations with only
 spontaneous fission sources and another set of simulations with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 sources in order to later adjust the proportion of one source type to the
 other.
 Since each of these sources creates histories which are independent from
 each other, Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y1_final"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y2_final"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:r2_final"

\end_inset

 can be easily rewritten with source differentiation by considering that
 the total contribution is the sum of each individual contribution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{R}_{1}=\mathring{Y}_{1}=\sum_{i}^{I}\left[S_{i}\sum_{N=1}^{\infty}p_{i,N}\cdot C_{N}^{1}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{R}_{2}=\sum_{i}^{I}\left[S_{i}\sum_{N=2}^{\infty}p_{i,N}\cdot C_{N}^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau)=\frac{\mathring{R}_{2,i}}{\tau}\,\intop_{0}^{\tau}dt\cdot cdf_{i}(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 denoting the contribution of the source of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 among 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 sources.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is still calculated through two times the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and no specific derivation is required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results and discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Case study
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case study is the Sub-critical Copper-Reflected 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-phase Plutonium (SCR
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

P) integral benchmark experiment designed and measured by the Los Alamos
 National Laboratory at the National Criticality Experiments Research Center
 (NCERC).
 The experiment is detailed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SCRaP Benchmark"

\end_inset

 and presented in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BeRP-ball-and"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Experimental-set-up."

\end_inset

.
 It consists in a weapon-grade plutonium sphere nested in various thicknesses
 of copper spherical shells and/or polyethylene spherical shells.
 Neutrons basically arise from spontaneous fissions and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions.
 The correlated neutron measurement were performed using a detector system
 made of 
\begin_inset Formula $He^{3}$
\end_inset

 tubes inside high density polyethylene.
 Among the 16 different measured configurations, this paper will focus on
 configuration number 15 which has the highest 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{eff}$
\end_inset

 value.
 It consists of the plutonium sphere surrounded by a first layer of polyethylene
 surrounded by 7 layers of copper.
 Choosing the configuration with the highest reactivity will make easier
 to distinguish the neutrons delayed part of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{eff}$
\end_inset

 of this configuration with the Monte Carlo code MORET 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MORET"

\end_inset

 developed at IRSN is about 0.944 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 = 100 pcm).
 
\end_layout

