\begin_layout Subsection
General procedure for the calculation of NMC values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general procedure used in this paper for the calculation of NMC values
 with the 
\emph on
analog method
\emph default
 is as follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step 1: A simulation is performed considering both types of neutron sources
 (spontaneous fissions and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions) and imposing that all histories start (i.e.
 the instant of the source event) at t = 0 second.
 The number of source events to be simulated must be sufficient for the
 duration of the desired signal.
 For each neutron detection in the two NOMAD detectors, the following informatio
n is recorded: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the type of source from which the neutron originated,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the detection time,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the history identifier.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The calculation has been performed using the version 6 of MORET - based
 on MORET
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

5 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MORET"

\end_inset

 - which allows the analog simulation of neutrons and the record of simulation
 information into list-mode like files.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
Step 2: From the output file is extracted for each type of source a number
 of histories corresponding to the desired signal duration and the intensity
 of each source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step 3: The beginning of each histories (and therefore the corresponding
 detection times) are modified by sampling from a uniform random law over
 the choosen signal duration interval.
 Some histories may start close enough to the end of the signal so that
 their detection times can appear beyond the chosen signal duration.
 To solve this, the modulo function of parameter the signal duration is
 applied on each detection time to confine the detection times to the desired
 time interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step 4: All detection times are merged to form the final signal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step 5: Other post-processing can be applied to simulate experimental instrument
ation behavior such as the detectors dead-time or the detectors time resolution.
 For this present work no experimental instrumentation effect is taken into
 account since the 
\emph on
direct method 
\emph default
cannot handle them for the time beeing and this step is skipped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Step 6: NMC values are calculated using post processing programs as for
 a signal originating from real detectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is several benefits to this approach for the 
\emph on
analog method
\emph default
.
 First, the simulation of the transport of one history is an independent
 process from the transport of other histories.
 Therefore, this approach does not necessarily require a parallelized computatio
n code and it is sufficient to run several instances of the computation
 code, taking care to modify the seed of the random generator.
 Secondly, it is possible to adjust the parameters used in post-processing
 (sources intensities, sources types, signal duration) to build a new signal
 without having to recalculate the transport part whose calculation time
 is much longer than that of the post-processing part.
 Another interesting point is the possibility to change the seed used to
 sample the beginning time of the histories (step 3).
 One can then create multiple signals that all contain the same knowledge
 (i.e.
 fission chains, detections, etc.) but distributed differently (although
 the uniform random law is still used).
 This allows the study of statistical properties (expected mean and standard
 deviation) of observable calculated from these signals.

\color blue
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding the 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
 the post processing program only needs the result of the first step for
 the calculation of the two required terms 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $pdf(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Since each recorded detection has been associated to its corresponding
 history identifier the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset

 is straightforward.
 The calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $pdf(t)$
\end_inset

, must be done taking into account all the combination of detections originating
 from a history as illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:any_pair_of_detection"

\end_inset

.
 It is important that the binning used to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $pdf(t)$
\end_inset

 is fine and cover a large time range in order to include both prompt and
 delayed neutrons.
 In the following comparison the binning is composed of 
\begin_inset Formula $1000$
\end_inset

 values logarithmicaly distributed between 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cdot10^{-9}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\cdot10^{4}$
\end_inset

 seconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/any pair of detection.svg.png
	lyxscale 75
	width 5cm

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:any_pair_of_detection"

\end_inset

All the combination of detections originating from a history must be taken
 into account for the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As seen from Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:y_final"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

 are link to each other, moreover as no discrepancy is expected for the
 single counting rate, this paper focus only on the comparisons between
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mean values comparison
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the SCR
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

P benchmark report 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SCRaP Benchmark"

\end_inset

 neutrons arise from approximately 128500 spontaneous fissions per second
 and 4200 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions per second.
 The duration of the simulated signal is about 5500 seconds which approximately
 represents 
\begin_inset Formula $7\cdot10^{8}$
\end_inset

 spontaneous fissions and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.3\cdot10^{7}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions.
 A first comparison is presented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
