\begin_layout Subsection
Variance comparison
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the time being, exact formula of the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 has not been yet established and estimation of this value is relying on
 multiple sets of histories.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Y_var_cmp"

\end_inset

 shows the variance as a function of the sets size expressed as the proportion
 of histories used to calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 from the previous plots (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Y-values"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comp_1000_signals"

\end_inset

).
 The samples width is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,s$
\end_inset

 and each variance value is calculated with 50 sets of histories.
 The blue line is a fit demonstrating that the variance varies as the inverse
 of the number of simulated histories.
 This is in contrast with the 
\emph on
analog method
\emph default
 whose the variance varies with the inverse of the number of samples.
 This figure also includes the uncertainty of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau\,=\,1\thinspace s)$
\end_inset

 from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comp_100_signals"

\end_inset

 as a red dashed line (with nominal sources intensities and with all the
 available histories).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account that the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau=1\thinspace s)$
\end_inset

 for the SCR
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

P experiment (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comp_100_signals"

\end_inset

) is about 0.8, this figure shows that the direct method has about the same
 variance as the analog method using about 0.1% of the total simulated histories.
 It has to be noted that this gain depends on many parameters which are
 not presented here due to the lack of theoretical formula of the direct
 method's variance.
 Nevertheless it is obvious that this gain increase with the intensity of
 the signal since the fission chains tends to overlap more and more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/plot6.png
	lyxscale 25
	width 7cm

\end_inset


